.TH PYREADER 1 "March 2026" "PyReader 1.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
pyreader \- an ncurses ebook reader supporting FB2 and EPUB formats
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B pyreader
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B PyReader
is a terminal-based ebook reader that supports FictionBook 2 (FB2) and EPUB formats.
It provides a simple ncurses interface for browsing, searching, and reading ebooks
in the terminal.
.PP
The application maintains a library of books from configured directories,
automatically rescans for new books on startup, and remembers reading positions
across sessions.
.SH FIRST RUN
On first launch, PyReader will prompt for the path to your books directory.
Enter the full path to a directory containing FB2 and/or EPUB files.
.PP
Additional library paths can be added later using Ctrl+L from the library view.
.SH LIBRARY VIEW
The library view displays a scrollable, alphabetically sorted list of all
discovered books. Each book is assigned a unique number for quick access.
.SS Library View Controls
.TP
.BR "Up Arrow / Down Arrow"
Navigate through the book list.
.TP
.BR "Page Up / Page Down"
Scroll the list by 10 entries.
.TP
.BR "Home"
Jump to the first book in the list.
.TP
.BR "End"
Jump to the last book in the list.
.TP
.BR "Enter"
Open the currently selected book.
.TP
.BR "0-9"
Type a book number, then press Enter to jump directly to that book.
.TP
.BR "Ctrl+W"
Activate search mode. Type a query and press Enter to search.
Search matches book titles, authors, or numeric IDs.
.TP
.BR "Ctrl+L"
Add a new library path. You will be prompted to enter a directory path.
.TP
.BR "ESC"
Press once to display exit warning. Press again to quit the application.
.TP
.BR "Q"
Same as ESC - displays exit warning, press again to quit.
.SH SEARCH MODE
Press Ctrl+W to enter search mode. The search bar will appear at the top
of the library view.
.SS Search Behavior
.IP \(bu 2
If the query is numeric, it matches the book ID number.
.IP \(bu 2
Otherwise, the query matches against book titles and author names
(case-insensitive substring match).
.IP \(bu 2
Press Enter to execute the search.
.IP \(bu 2
Press ESC to cancel and return to the full book list.
.SS Search Results
After searching, the book list is filtered to show only matching results.
Navigate and open books as in the normal library view.
To clear the search and view all books, press Ctrl+W then Enter with an
empty query, or press ESC.
.SH READER VIEW
The reader view displays the book content with automatic text wrapping
to fit the terminal width. The current page and total pages are shown
at the bottom of the screen.
.SS Reader View Controls
.TP
.BR "Right Arrow / Down Arrow / Page Down / N"
Advance to the next page.
.TP
.BR "Left Arrow / Up Arrow / Page Up / P"
Go back to the previous page.
.TP
.BR "Space"
Scroll down by one line (slower navigation within a page).
.TP
.BR "Home"
Jump to the first page of the book.
.TP
.BR "End"
Jump to the last page of the book.
.TP
.BR "ESC / Q"
Close the current book and return to the library view. The current
reading position is automatically saved.
.SH CONFIGURATION
Configuration is stored in
.I ~/.pyreader_config.json
and includes:
.IP \(bu 2
Library paths (list of directories to scan)
.IP \(bu 2
Last opened book file path
.IP \(bu 2
Last reading position (page number)
.PP
This file is created automatically and should not be edited manually
unless the application is not running.
.SH SUPPORTED FORMATS
.SS FictionBook 2 (FB2)
Full support for FB2 files including:
.IP \(bu 2
Title and author extraction from metadata
.IP \(bu 2
Paragraph and section rendering
.IP \(bu 2
Subtitle formatting
.SS EPUB
Support for EPUB files including:
.IP \(bu 2
Title and author extraction from OPF metadata
.IP \(bu 2
HTML content parsing and text extraction
.IP \(bu 2
Reading order determined from OPF spine
.PP
Note: EPUB support focuses on text content. Complex formatting,
images, and tables may not render optimally.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B TERM
Terminal type. PyReader requires a terminal with ncurses support.
Common compatible terminals include xterm, gnome-terminal, konsole,
alacritty, and tmux.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I ~/.pyreader_config.json
User configuration file containing library paths and reading positions.
.SH TIPS
.IP 1. 4
Use the number jump feature for quick access: type the book number
and press Enter.
.IP 2. 4
Organize books in directories by author or genre, then add multiple
library paths with Ctrl+L.
.IP 3. 4
The application remembers your last position, so you can quit and
resume reading later from the same page.
.IP 4. 4
Resize your terminal to change text wrapping. The book will be
repaginated automatically.
.IP 5. 4
Search supports partial matches - you don't need to type the full title.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Successful program execution.
.TP
.B 1
Error during initialization or terminal setup.
